title: For Sale:  M1 Garand - SA 5.79 - AFPG - NM Air Force Premium Grade Semi Automatic Rifle.
postcontent: Air Force Premium Grade (AFPG) NM M-1 Garand. These were built into match rifles by USAF armorers at the USAF Competitive Weapons Shop at Lackland AFB. Very few AFPG Garands made it into civilian hands, far fewer than Navy B's as it was common for the AF team member to "acquire" their rifles upon retirement and very few were sold to state shooting associations and clubs through the DCM. After the largest supporter of the competitive marksmanship in the USAF, Gen. Curtis LeMay, passed away the USAF NM rifle program died off. The USAF then turned most of the remaining AFPG M1s into drill rifles (welded and plugged barrels) or parade rifles (refinished for appearances). You can read more about this rare variant of the M1 rifle in the Garand Collectors Association Journal vol. 26 No.3 Summer 2012 issue. This AFPG was built using a Springfield Armory 5.79 receiver. The block started at 5793848 and ended at 5799999. There were only 6152 SA receivers produced in this serial number block which makes it unique and highly sought after. The barrel drawing number is SA 7791035, which was produced for the 1963 National Match rifles. The barrel is marked “80-06” in marker on the top. The area where the lower band sits has been knurled. The barrel has been highly polished from the drawing numbers all the way around to the clip latch side. It’s been polished smooth and is so shiny that you can see your reflection. Super tight barrel. MW 0+ TE 2. The rear sight is a standard base that has been modified. The right side of the receiver ear where the windage knob goes has also been highly polished. The receiver has been modified for half clicks of windage. A hole has been drilled into the receiver where a bolt extractor spring and plunger sit. The Wright windage knob has 8 grooves machined into it to give ½ minute windage adjustments. The aperture is a 520 national match.The gas cylinder has been modified to national match specifications with the rear ring reamed and the tab modified. The front sight blade has been narrowed. The stock has been fully bedded and has an exceptionally tight fit just into the receiver. The lockup is tight as well. The stock ferrule has been modified. The lower band has been reamed. The op rod is a NM 7790722-RA. This was an AFPG barreled receiver that was restored. I think I have the CMP Certificate which the previous owner sent with the barreled receiver. I have personally shot this rifle and it functioned just great. Kept them all in the black on a 100 yard SR-1 target
